{"title_page": "Camilla Marcus", "text_new": "[[File:Camilla Marcus.jpg|thumb|Camilla Marcus, Chef & Restaurateur, in 2020]]\n{{short description|American chef and restaurateur}}\n'''Camilla Marcus''' is a New York chef, restaurateur and advocate. She owns west~bourne, a zero-waste vegetarian restaurant in New York's SoHo neighborhood that operates with a fully integrated philanthropic business model. In 2020 during the [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry in the United States|coronavirus pandemic closures]], Marcus led the formation of the lobbying group [[Independent Restaurant Coalition|Independent Restaurant Coalition,]] an organization dedicated to advocating for the rights of independent restaurants through national legislative action. She also co-founded the fundraising organization ROAR to raise relief funds for laid-off restaurant workers<ref>{{cite web |url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/camilla-marcus-too-small-to-fail-too-big-to-ignore/id1503511166?i=1000469960554}}</ref>.\n\n== Early life ==\nMarcus was born and raised in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/worldwise-restaurateur-camilla-marcus-favorite-things-in-n-y-beyond-01557335723|title=Worldwise: Restaurateur Camilla Marcus\u2019 Favorite Things in N.Y. & Beyond|last=Magers|first=Michael|website=www.barrons.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> She holds a business degree from [[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania|Wharton]], an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]]/[[Juris Doctor|JD]] from [[New York University School of Law|New York University]], and a culinary arts degree from the [[International Culinary Center]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://stories.zagat.com/posts/the-mindful-restaurant-revolution-of-camilla-marcus-west-bourne-new-york|title=The Mindful Restaurant Revolution Of Camilla Marcus|website=Zagat Stories|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dietdetective.com/chefs-who-cook-well-and-do-good-camilla-marcus/|title=Chefs Who Cook Well and Do Good: Camilla Marcus|date=2019-10-16|website=Diet Detective|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://intothegloss.com/2018/08/camilla-marcus-west-bourne-interview/|title=West-bourne's Camilla Marcus Is A Bi-Coastal Spa Enthusiast|date=2018-08-02|website=Into The Gloss|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMarcus began her career at Dell'anima<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nylon.com/articles/west-bourne-camilla-marcus-interview|title=West~bourne: A Sustainable Restaurant That\u2019s About More Than Just The Straws|date=2018-08-09|website=NYLON|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and later worked with [[Tom Colicchio]] on the opening of his restaurant Riverpark.<ref name=\":3\" /> Later she served as Director of Business Development for [[Danny Meyer]]'s company, [[Union Square Hospitality Group]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.specialtyfood.com/news/article/12-under-35-camilla-marcus-founder-west-bourne/|title=12 Under 35: Camilla Marcus, founder, West-Bourne|date=2019-09-01|website=Specialty Food Association|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Marcus has also worked in real estate investing for Colony Capital and CIM Group<ref>{{Cite web|title=west~bourne|url=https://www.westbourne.com/philosophy/|website=www.westbourne.com|language=en|access-date=2020-05-04}}</ref>.\n\nMarcus founded west~bourne, a restaurant in [[SoHo, Manhattan|SoHo]], in January of 2018.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wandpdesign.com/blogs/the-fresh-squeeze/camilla-marcus-westbourne-lunch-interview|title=Camilla Marcus' Sustainable SoHo|last=|first=|date=|website=W&P|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://wwd.com/eye/lifestyle/giving-back-through-food-camilla-marcus-opens-west-bourne-in-soho-11092235/|title=Giving Back Through Food: Camilla Marcus Opens \u2018West-bourne\u2019 in SoHo|last=Nordstrom|first=Leigh|last2=|first2=|date=2018-01-10|website=WWD|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womansday.com/author/10635/womans-day-kitchen/|title=Woman's Day Kitchen|website=Woman's Day|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Marcus is also the Co-Founder of TechTable, a hospitality thought leadership platform<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.techtablesummit.com/about/#our-founders}}</ref>, and a partner of Pound for Pound Consulting, a boutique strategic and creative agency for hospitality-related initiatives<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.poundforpoundconsulting.com/#meet-the-team}}</ref>.\n\nShe was named one of the [[PureWow]] 100 in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.purewow.com/purewow100/camilla-marcus|title=Camilla Marcus - 2018 Honoree {{!}} PureWow 100|website=www.purewow.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nIn 2020 during the [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry in the United States|coronavirus pandemic closures]], Marcus led several advocacy initiatives. She is a co-founder of Relief Opportunities for All Restaurants (ROAR), a coalition formed to support independent restaurant owners and operators in New York State<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u200eTAKE AWAY ONLY: CAMILLA MARCUS: \"TOO SMALL TO FAIL, TOO BIG TO IGNORE\" on Apple Podcasts|url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/camilla-marcus-too-small-to-fail-too-big-to-ignore/id1503511166?i=1000469960554|website=Apple Podcasts|language=en-us|access-date=2020-05-04}}</ref>. She is also a founding member of the lobbying group [[Independent Restaurant Coalition]] (IRC), an organization dedicated to advocating for the rights of independent restaurants through national legislative action<ref>{{Cite web|title=To Save Their Industry, Restaurant Owners Get Organized|url=https://www.grubstreet.com/2020/03/nyc-restaurant-organizations-roar-irc.html|last=Greenwald|first=Kitty|date=2020-03-25|website=Grub Street|language=en-us|access-date=2020-05-04}}</ref>. \n\n== Business Model ==\nwest~bourne is a restaurant that celebrates Camilla's upbringing in Los Angeles and is inspired by [[California]]'s craftsmanship, culinary heritage and emphasis on sustainability. The restaurant operates with a fully integrated philanthropic business model. The restaurant employs no porters or dishwashers, and all employees enter at the same level and are cross trained to do all jobs.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/a28967312/women-changing-future/|title=For Our 25th Anniversary, We're Celebrating 25 Women Who Are Changing the Future|last=|first=|date=2019-09-24|website=Marie Claire|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> west~bourne donates 1% of revenues to The Door, an organization which provides hospitality industry training for youth.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> In October of 2019 she partnered with Vivvi, a child care center in New York City, to offer her employees subsidized childcare from 7am to 2 am, weekdays and weekends.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ny.eater.com/2019/10/18/20920652/free-childcare-restaurant-industry-camilla-marcus|title=Could Free, After-Hours Child Care Be a Possibility for Restaurant Workers?|last=Kludt|first=Amanda|date=2019-10-18|website=Eater NY|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cherrybombe.com/radio-cherry-bombe/camilla-marcus-wants-to-change-the-restaurant-world|title=Camilla Marcus Wants to Change the Restaurant World|website=Cherry Bombe|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/accessible-child-care-new-york-city|title=Meet the Restaurateur Championing Accessible Childcare for New York City\u2019s Hospitality Workers|last=Adrian-Diaz|first=Jenna|website=Vogue|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> west~bourne is a zero-waste restaurant. As of February 2020, the restaurant was in the process of earning a zero-waste certification from Green Business Certification, Inc<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/innovation/rise-zero-waste-restaurants-180974394/}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marcus, Camilla}}\n[[Category:American restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:People from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:New York University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:International Culinary Center alumni]]\n[[Category:American chefs]]\n[[Category:Women chefs]]\n[[Category:Women restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American chef and restaurateur}}\n'''Camilla Marcus''' is a New York chef, restaurateur and advocate. She owns west~bourne, a zero-waste vegetarian restaurant in New York's SoHo neighborhood that operates with a fully integrated philanthropic business model. In 2020 during the [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry in the United States|coronavirus pandemic closures]], Marcus led the formation of the lobbying group [[Independent Restaurant Coalition]] to try to save the independent restaurant industry. She also co-founded the fundraising organization ROAR to raise relief funds for laid-off restaurant workers<ref>{{cite web |url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/camilla-marcus-too-small-to-fail-too-big-to-ignore/id1503511166?i=1000469960554}}</ref>.\n\n== Early life ==\nMarcus was born and raised in Los Angeles.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/worldwise-restaurateur-camilla-marcus-favorite-things-in-n-y-beyond-01557335723|title=Worldwise: Restaurateur Camilla Marcus\u2019 Fa